gpie + geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank()) + geom_text(aes(y = Frequency/3 + c(0, cumsum(Frequency)[-length(Frequency)]),

# map coordinates
all_coord = p1$tweet_coord[!is.na(p1$tweet_coord)] # remove nas
all_coord = all_coord[-5] # remove rows containing [0,0]
all_coord = as.character(all_coord)
all_coord = substr(all_coord, 2, nchar(all_coord)-1)

location = data.frame(lat = as.numeric(), long = as.numeric())
for (a in all_coord) {
  lat = as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(a,"[,]")))[1]
  #print(lat)
  long = as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(a, "[,]")))[2]
  #print(long)
  location = rbind(location, c(lat,long))
}
colnames(location) = c('lat','long')

require(maps)
## Loading required package: maps
world_map <- map_data("world")
g1 = ggplot()
g1 = g1 + geom_polygon(data=world_map, aes(x=long, y=lat, group = group), colour="black", fill = 'lightblue') + 
  ggtitle("Location of tweets across the World")
g1 = g1 + geom_point(data=location, aes(x=long, y=lat, size = 1), color="coral1") + scale_size(name="Total Tweets")
g1 + ylim(-50, 80)

#isolate US only
USdata<-sumData[c(3:11,28,31,58,63),]
states <- map_data("state")
g2 = ggplot()

  ggtitle("Location of tweets across the States")
g2 = g2 + geom_point(data=location, aes(x=long, y=lat, size = 1), color="coral1") + scale_size(name="Total Tweets")
g2 + xlim(-125, -65) + ylim(25, 50)
